segments.text: County Engineering Department.
Today's date is September 4th, 1981.
Dr. Hawkins, let us begin by your telling something about your early years in Kentucky.
Well, as I said, I was born in a little coal mining town called Weeksbury, Kentucky.
That's W-E-E-K-S-B-U-R-Y.
It was a town of about a
thousand people, no less than that probably.
Typical Eastern Kentucky coal mining town.
My dad in early years was a engineer in the sense of a railroad engineer.
He ran the power plant and then he got in the grocery store business and I grew up in that environment.
My dad was a merchant.
During the
World War II years, we moved to Louisville, Kentucky.
My father worked for DuPont.
After World War II, we moved back to eastern Kentucky to a different town called Wheelwright.
That's W-A-T-E-L-W-R-I-G-H-T. One word?
Yes.
It was a different coal mining town, and my dad went back into the
grocery business, and I finished, or grew up in that environment, finished high school there.
Well, actually I didn't finish high school.
I went through the junior year, and I was lucky enough to receive a Ford Foundation scholarship, which was an experimental program at the time.
What year was this?
Let's see, that must have been about 54.
Sounds about right.
Plus or minus a year.
Been a while.
And so I missed my senior year in high school and went to University of Louisville.
The program was to test the relevance of the senior year in high school.
I struggled through those years.
Of course, I came from a small country school.
Went to college without all the necessary preparation in chemistry and physics and trigonometry.
So it was an interesting experience.
I survived.
University of Louisville was a very fine engineering school, majored in mechanical engineering.
Went through their co-op program, and after about
I guess two and a half years, I was going on another co-op program.
And I happened to visit home.
And my former principal of the high school I graduated from, or finished in, persuaded me to teach high school for a year.
He convinced me that was a better experience than a co-op.
It was an experience.
When did you complete?
Did you complete the bachelor's program in engineering
University of Louisville?
No.
I was going on a co-op period.
I was probably two and a half years into the program.
And so when I went back to teach high school, at that time, Louisville was a quite intense school, and I guess I had an equivalent of about 104 or 105 semester hours.
And that was sufficient for a high school teaching certificate, a temporary certificate.
And so, like I said, my principal convinced me that
that was better experience than co-op.
And so I taught high school for a year.
What year was that, 57, 58?
Sounds about right.
What did you teach, science?
Taught mathematics, algebra, geometry, and biology.
Was it difficult to attract teachers in that part of the state?
Probably not during that time.
They just had ended up with an opening.
And I was passing through town at that time.
And it looked like a reasonably good experience.
It was, like I said.
How were you when you were teaching?
Well, that was the interesting part.
Let's see, I was, because I left high school a year early, I was probably about, I went to college when I was 17, so I was about 19 probably.
maybe 20.
Did you have some of the students who were older than you?
Yeah.
And of course, a lot of my friends who I had known as freshmen were still always teaching them.
So it was an interesting experience.
Did they take advantage of the attempt to?
No.
No.
In fact, I guess I was, like all young people, a rebel.
And the principal and I had some disagreement.
I think I ended up flunking about half of the mathematics classes.
I don't think I failed anybody in biology, because my attitude was they probably, I probably was not an expert in biology, but I figured I knew mathematics.
And I was persuaded to, or tried to convince me that really we shouldn't be flunking people.
And I guess that was where I got my first experience to my ideas about what was wrong with education, that the philosophy was that maybe we ought to keep them off the street.
don't agree with that philosophy, and I still don't.
And I think education is a privilege.
But I finished school then.
I mean, finished teaching school.
And of course, when I prepared to re-enter University of Louisville, because I had taught, I had gotten out of sequence in co-op.
And so what happened, I didn't go back this summer.
I worked that summer.
I had prepared to go back in the fall and pick up where I went, where I left off.
And I got on the wrong co-op sequence.
And University of Louisville, the way it was, the way they ran the program is there was two different classes.
And if you went on, you staggered them.
And so it would have been necessary to stay away a year or a quarter.
So I decided to transfer schools and went to University of Kentucky.
And so I finished, got my B.S.
at University of Kentucky in mechanical engineering.
What year was that?
It was 1960.
I must have started at 55.
I can't remember.
It took five years to go through with teaching.
When you were teaching school that year, do you remember what your salary was?
I have no idea.
I was curious for a comparison purposes.
It probably was under $3,000 a year.
I wouldn't have the slightest idea.
Okay, you completed your B.S.
from the University of Kentucky.
Yes.
Where?
Lexington?
Lexington.
In 1960, a mechanical engineer.
1960, right.
Okay, how did the experiences with your father and some parts of his relationship with coal mining, how did this affect your career choice?
Did that have anything to do with it?
Well, I guess most engineers, you tend to be,
mechanically inclined.

I suppose in my, some facts about engineering, I think it's changed now, but up until this generation, most engineering students are typically the first child in the family to get a college education.
It's typically the first professional programs.
And also a lot of
young men at that time went into the program because they liked machinery.
They liked automobiles.
That's what got me there.
You related to automobiles and trains and airplanes as being what you were involved in.
And when I got the Ford Foundation scholarship, the scholarship required a science education.
And basically my choices were physics, mathematics, or engineering.
And I chose engineering primarily because of the association with machinery.
Young people usually go into engineering thinking that they're going to immediately build cars.
And you find out that engineering really is very mathematically oriented and not what you thought it was.
But usually by the time you're halfway through, it's too late to back out.
But in any case, I graduated University of Kentucky in 1960.
Where did you get your master's degree?
I studied at University of Kentucky.
I probably am like most young people.
I got a master's degree because somebody asked me to.
And being young and naive at the time, I was very flattered.
But at the time, we had an old German fella.
called Carl Otto Lang.
And along with my senior year, I had the opportunity to take a class from him.
And he flattered me by saying that I should stay in graduate school.
And that was a bit different than it is now when we try to get everybody into graduate school.
So I did stay, and he was director of what was called the Wintergren Aeronautical Lab.
It's W-E-N-N-E-R hyphen G-R-E-N. And Wintergren is, the money was donated.
Wintergren happened to be the man who was behind the Electrolux Corporation.
And his nationality, it seemed that he was European.
I think he was possibly Swiss or whatever.
But he donated a laboratory, and I understand during World War II there was some question about his allegiance and some cloud over the whole thing.
But in any case, Dr. Lang was the director of the lab.
At that time, most of the work we were doing, they were doing, was in bioengineering.
And so I went to work for him and got involved in the bioengineering program, got interested in that program, did a lot of work in...
All over everything.
I'll tell you a bit about the work, but the laboratory was under contract of the Air Force, and we were doing work in human tolerance studies, tolerance to acceleration and vibration.
We were also doing a program of training chimpanzees for space flight at that time.
I was not directly involved in the chimpanzee training program.
My involvement was in the human tolerance side.
Very interesting experience.
We spent probably half our time at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton doing experimental work on human subjects.
And of course, about half time in research at the University in Lexington.
And I finished that program.
1961, and by that time I failed to mention that I was married a couple of years earlier.
We had a child and felt that we couldn't afford to go on to pursue a PhD.
Had had to borrow money to get as far as I was, so we were forced to go to industry.
I guess I made my mind up about the time I entered graduate school that I would eventually get a PhD.
When did you finish the MA?
In 62?
It took a year and a half.
December of 61, I think it was.
Okay, and then what company did you work for?
I went to work at Pratt & Whitney Aircraft first.
It's P-R-A-T-T and W-H-I-T-N-E-Y Aircraft.
And Pratt & Whitney is one of the two major jet engine manufacturers.
Is that in California?
No.
Pratt
the home or the base operations in Connecticut.
But they had recently built a research and development center in Florida.
So I went with their research and development center in Florida.
That's West Palm Beach.
I went into what they call their applied research division.
And probably 10 people when I arrived and
150 when I left.
So I was there during most of the growth years.
I suppose I stayed with Pratt & Whitney about three years.
I'm not good at dates.
And left Pratt & Whitney and went to Huntsville, Alabama with Chrysler Corporation and their space division.
Headed up a group of engineers there.
Worked for Chrysler about a similar amount of time and decided that it was time to get serious about education again.
I ended up going from Chrysler Corporation to Brown Engineering for several reasons.
One is some dissatisfaction with Chrysler management.
a better opportunity and a better opportunity to go to school.
Where was this at?
It's in Huntsville.
They were both in Huntsville.
So I started back to school and going at nights and I took over University of Alabama in Huntsville is where I started.
Taking a course at night, this seemed difficult with the job I had.
I was in management.
And so I asked Brown to transfer me to the research division so that I would not have to be involved with people to pursue my education.
And they did.
So I had the opportunity to work by myself on my own projects.
And I guess I went for another year trying to take courses at night and decided that was not the way to get an advanced education.
And ultimately went back to school full time at the University of Alabama at Tuscaloosa.
and graduated with a PhD in engineering mechanics in 1969.
Went from there to West Virginia University in Morgantown.
Spent six years there as a professor, associate professor, mechanical engineering.
Well, actually, that's not quite correct.
When I first went to school there, it was a, they had a department of theoretical and applied mechanics, which is where I joined.
After about three years, I guess I remember, the department was combined with the mechanical engineering department.
The mechanical engineering department head stepped down for whatever reason, I don't know.
And the decision was made to combine departments, and the department head who was
And the mechanics department became the head of the combined department.
So we were mechanical engineering and mechanics.
But anyway, I stayed there for six years.
Got involved in a lot of different research areas.
Left there and went to Memphis State University as department chairman.
Stayed there two years and came here in your four years.
In 1977, you came here?
Is that four years ago?
That's what it would be.
How did you happen to come to Texas A&M?
Well, the job was open.
It was advertised.
I can't remember whether I was recommended or applied, but essentially applied.
And I was offered the job.
You came in what capacity?
Department head.
You came directly as department head?
What are some of the duties that you undertake now as department head, just generally?
Well, of all the things, I guess it's probably the most difficult to talk about is what I do as department head.
I suppose it's more appropriate to find out what you want to know in this interview.
Obviously, we could talk for the rest of the week about various aspects of my life.

It might be well, let me ask you again, what are you really trying to get out of the interview as far as we've gone through a brief, or do you want to concentrate on the past history or recent history?
Just what you've experienced as you've been here now since we got up to this point.
Well, I think it would be well to talk a little bit about the department and A&M as I see it.
From my perspective, A&M, as you well know, is an old school.
And I like to explain to people as a college, it's 105 years old or whatever.
As a university, it's maybe 20.
So A&M is a university very much in transition.
from numbers, because of its goals, its place in society, its attitudes about itself.
To tell you an experience, when I interviewed for the job, I had a I happened to be interviewing at the time when
The department was having the Pytos Sigma banquet.
That's our honorary society.
Pytos Sigma's Greek letter is P-I-T-A-U-S-I-G-E-M-A.
That's the Mechanical Engineering Honorary Society.
The reason the job was opening, the individual who was in the job was retiring, Cliff Semaine.
And Clifford had been in the job.
About 24 years, best I can remember.
I'm interviewing him first.
OK.
So Cliff, are you interviewing Charlie Crawford?
I haven't set that one up yet.
Do.
The most important one of all three of us is Charlie Crawford.
But in any case, the interesting thing about that, I was first impressed
that someone had survived as a department head for 24 years.
That's even more amazing now that I really know what it means to be department head at A&M.
But at the banquet, he went and introduced me to somebody.
And he introduced me to Charlie Crawford.
And Charlie was department head for maybe 27 years.
I need to talk to Charlie about that.
The impressive thing about meeting those two men standing in the same place, that represented a half a century of this department.
And that period represented a lot of changes, but not the drastic ones.
Tremendous history.
And not only did it represent a half a century of the department, but also half of the whole
history of the department, was standing there and two living men.
I remember my comment at the time, I said I certainly wanted a job, because obviously you live forever.
It must be an easy job, but I found out it really wasn't.
But A&M, up until that time, was a relatively, from my perception, a relatively stable organization.
I guess the university changed presidents and
relatively often, like most universities do.
But department heads were in place for a long period of time.
Deans had generally long enough time to put programs into effect.
And the administration was stable.
Cliffs of Maine, quite literally, is a giant of a man, if you haven't met Cliff.
He's an imposing figure.
He's about 6'4".
a fine man, but characteristically probably as different from me as one could get in that Cliff ran the department like A&M was run, had been run for a hundred years.
He was a retired general in reserve.
He ran the department with a lot of discipline and with
very much the way I would suppose that A&M as a college was run 20 years earlier.
From my perception, A&M came into the 20th century a step at a time.
They made the transition literally of a department at a time, which I think was very appropriate.
No one seemed to be in a great haste.
I think our dean, Dean Benson, which I really think is probably
in my estimation, a real giant of a man, shows the time when Glyphosate of Maine retired to make a change in the department.
As you may know, we are organized both as a department and as a research division.
As an example, this department is a division of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station and also a department of mechanical engineering.
Right now, I hold both titles.
I'm the head of the Mechanical Engineering Department.
I'm also head of the Mechanical Engineering Division of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
Cliff was not.
This duty was shared by another individual.
So he concentrated on the academic program, primarily the undergraduate program.
When I came, my charge from Fred Benson was quite simple.
It was a two-paragraph charge to build a graduate research program of
equal quality to our undergraduate program and to concentrate on those research areas that are important to the state of Texas.
And I repeat that.
Whatever chance I get when I'm asked what our goals are, I say that's what our goals are.
I see no reason to change it.
I think it's what we're in business for.
But quite obviously, the need for building research and graduate programs and reputations of the university, the college within the university,
in the department within the college was important for several reasons.
One is, from my perception, when you're a relatively small college, you can assume a role quite differently than when you're a major university.
People perceive you differently.
They perceive quality differently.
When you suddenly become the largest college of engineering
possibly in the world, certainly in the nation.
The largest department of mechanical engineering is not sufficient to just do undergraduate education.
People start measuring you against your peer group.
And of course, I think our peer group happen to be schools, large state schools like Purdue and Georgia Tech and Illinois and Virginia Tech.
And so the outside world, whether it's other students, whether it's the community,
or whether it's the government, a perceived quality of where you stand in your peer groups.
So we said as a major objective was to fulfill this particular role and build our research of the quality and quantity that would be expected in the University Department of Science.
When I came, I guess the department was, within the college, very near the bottom in research.
To tell you some statistics, we have grown in enrollment from a little over 800 to about 1,700 this fall.
So we've just about doubled in enrollment.
In four years.
In four years.
In the graduate enrollment, it's grown about 300%.
We've about tripled the graduate enrollment.
about 30 to a little over 90.
In research, we've gone from about 200,000 to a little over 2 million.
So we've grown about 1,000% in research.
We've more than doubled our faculty, which is not sufficient, obviously, because we've gone from a faculty, I don't remember the exact number, from about 30 to, I suppose right now,
We have two unfilled positions, but we would be about 69, 67, somewhere in there.
I'm embarrassed to say I can't remember.
So the faculty is doubled with almost covering the undergraduate enrollment, but it doesn't cover the tremendous expansion in the research program.
This research now puts the department second in the college.
We like to point out that we're second to civil engineering, which is very heavily involved with the Texas Transportation Institute.
So we've done quite well in meeting our goals.
Our faculty publications have gone from about, the data's hard to get from four years ago, but two or three per year to this year, about 100.
And so this faculty, of course, I'm very proud of.
But I think it's an extremely productive faculty.
I spend most of my time trying to get people to recognize the tremendous productivity of this faculty.
We have a teaching load that's about double any other college of engineering, Department of Mechanical Engineering in the state.
We teach about twice as much as a typical faculty at the University of Houston or University of Texas.
How much is that, 12 hours?
Our average teaching load has gone down
to about 10 hours, but only because our class sizes have gone up to over 200.
So we're really, our teaching load is still there.
We haven't been able to be very honest.
I'm not convinced yet that this is the direction to go in large classes.
This is an experiment that was very much suggested by our dean, and we're trying to see an effect.
The data is not all in, but I'm not pleased with it.
So in any case, the department has gone through a tremendous transition, not without some growing pains.
We've lost several of the faculty who were here for a long time.
We've had several people decide to choose careers in industry.
So we have a very young faculty that probably, I suppose, in the short four years, I've hired about 75% of the faculty.
So the department is one that's in transition.
We've started numerous new programs.
Our research programs, well, they're quite broad.
We can go in detail.
But essentially, every program that's ongoing is new.
It's less than four years old.
So we've changed from predominantly an undergraduate department to what we hope is becoming a much more balanced graduate research and undergraduate education department.
But you said mechanical engineering has the second highest enrollment in the Department of Engineering.
No, no.
I think we have the highest enrollment.
You compared it as second to civil engineering in what capacity?
In dollars of research.
Now, in numbers of students,
We have more students, significantly more students, than any degree-granting program in the college, significantly more.
The industrial engineering department is a conglomerate of computer science, industrial engineering, safety engineering, and bioengineering.
And I think collectively, they probably have as many or a few more students than we do.
As an example, I don't know the exact figures, but the industrial engineering program may be 400 students to our 1,700.
Computer science may be 1,000.
They may be more.
I don't know.
Bio may be a couple hundred.
Collectively, they're an equivalent science department.
These new faculty people that you have hired, what are some of the institutions that they have come from?
Oh, let me think.
Just say over the last two years.
I can remember.
I'd have to look up the rest of them.
Well, we have faculty from Berkeley, from MIT, from Virginia Tech.
from Penn State, from Ohio State, from Purdue, Oklahoma State, University of Texas, Lehigh, Georgia Tech.
Let me pause a minute and start to think of individuals.
University of Illinois.
I would say
that of the people that we brought into the department during the last four years, 85% to 90% are from what would be considered the top 10 engineering schools.
And the only school in the state, for example, well, I would say that the only schools I can recall that would not be considered in the top 10 would be we hired one fellow from SMU.
I don't know if I mentioned Berkeley.
We have a couple of guys from Berkeley, from USC, University of Southern California.
We have a guy on the staff now from the Technion in Israel.
Can you spell that?
Can't.
Technion is, I would consider, the best technical university in Israel and one of the best in the world.
It's certainly equivalent to our best engineering schools.
Do you have very many women enrolling in mechanical engineering?
It's increasing yearly.
I'd say our overall average is somewhere around close to 15%.
Each class is a little larger than the other.
I would say overall now it's about 15%.
The freshman enrollment may be up to around 20%, 25%.
It increases each year.
Do you find that women students enrolling are...
in about the same capacity as the male students?
No, I think they're superior.
In what regard?
Every regard, intellectually.
I'm talking on the average.
I would say also I would point out that I've been department head or chairman of two universities.
This makes a total of six years.
I think this is the first year that the American Society of Mechanical Engineering student chapter has not been chaired by a woman.
And this is an elective position by the students.
And this says something about their leadership ability and aggressiveness.
And so it's not just a matter of a good student intellectually.
The females that are coming to engineering, obviously, it takes a little bit more of aggression and desire to break into a male-dominated field.
So the women that are choosing engineering
My personal feeling is not necessarily the cross-section of the female population, but the ones that have the better mental ability, but also the higher desire and motivation.
And it's proving that way in class.
I don't think my personal feeling is, I think on a whole you'd find the male and female population about the same, but right now those who are choosing engineering are certainly the pioneering type.
Why do you have so few blacks who enroll in engineering programs?
I have no idea.
Absolutely none.
I may have personal opinions, but they're worthless.
Are you talking about at A&M or in general?
Either.
My personal feeling is A&M, we are somehow, we have to bring Prairie View in as a factor.
I think the students who choose to go to this system look at the
opportunity to go to Prairie View A&M or Texas A&M, and both have engineering schools.
And those who choose to go to engineering have to make a choice of one of the two.
I don't know how that relates, but I'm sure it must relate.
And I'm sure that must somehow influence the decision of a young black of saying, do I go to school that's

has an engineering program, is very oriented toward my culture and my race, or do I go to a school which has a great reputation but is predominantly white, maybe doesn't understand my culture or my problems?
And I don't know how that affects a student.
I haven't sat down and quizzed one.
But a personal opinion that must enter into decision making.
I think all engineering schools that blacks do not choose engineering as a career
as readily as they do others.
Again, you have opinions.
I think a lot of it is you hear people say role models.
I think role models has definitely a factor.
I think preparation is a factor.
I think in the past, I think black students have not necessarily got an equivalent education or been encouraged to take science and mathematics as a preparation force.
for college, and it's certainly necessary.
I guess I question one thing I don't understand.
As I mentioned earlier, in the past, people who chose engineering were typically the first child in the family that was college educated.
And of course, in the black community, this is a similar situation to what you saw in the farm communities a generation or two ago.
But it seems that many of the blacks are choosing business or one of the other professions as the first profession as opposed to engineering.
So why the change, I don't know.
What salary levels do starting mechanical engineers command today?
In the neighborhood of $25,000 a year.
Do people with higher degrees expect higher salaries?
Yes.
How much?
A master's degree, and these should not be taken as exact figures.
They're available if we want them.
But a master's degree typically is $1,500 to $2,000 a year or more.
A PhD, it's hard to put a figure on it because it's so much variation with individuals and where they go and desire.
But I would say a PhD might average, and this is my personal guess, another $5,000 a year or more starting salary than a BS so that he
a BS maybe 25, a master's maybe 27, a PhD around 30 to 32, somewhere in there.
What are some of the companies that mechanical engineering graduates from here would go to work for?
I would take the rest of the day.
Just a few of the major, a couple or three of the major ones?
Oh, here, of course, in the chemical companies, all of them.
Selenese, Dow, DuPont, Monsanto, and, of course, in the petroleum companies, all of them.
Exxon, Shell, Gulf.
What type of reputation do A&M graduates of engineering have in industry?
The undergraduates, I think, second to none.
I base that on, obviously, what recruiters tell me and what my friends in the industry tell me.
And I'm convinced that our undergraduates in engineering in general, and certainly mechanical, have a...
Extremely high reputation.
Our graduate students are good.
I can't say that people would come to A&M and see a graduate student, say, above MIT.
But it would be just the opposite in undergraduate.
And I think there's reasons for it.
I think our students, well, clearly, as I tell my students, we don't have better faculty.
We have better students.
And I believe that.
We get a better product in the front door, and we end up with a better product leaving.
So what makes our students better?
Several things.
We get a good student.
Intellectually, he's as good or better than any other student in engineering.
His motivation is by far better than any school I've been associated with.
I get the impression that kids don't come to A&M and College Station and have a good time.
I feel the decisions are made back in high school.
If they're looking for a social experience, they don't necessarily choose A&M.
Choose University of Texas or someone else.
We work our students hard, and our curriculum is a little bit longer than most.
So our students end up with mechanical engineering almost a semester longer than, say, the average, the national average.
So really, when you get an A&M mechanical engineer, he is better because he has a little bit more education than the average BS graduate.
How many hours is it take to complete the TAC engineering program?
It's 140 right now.
Okay, would you discuss some of the research projects that are underway or that have just been completed?
Oh, okay.
I'll discuss areas rather than projects.
We organized
the department about three, reorganized.
Basically, the department about three years ago was a department with one organizational structure, no subunits.
And of course, I fully believe 30 people, good management shows you that you can't really interact with 30 people effectively, and that's where we were.
And I saw where we were going, too.
So we reorganized into four major areas.
And we've designated those areas as design, mechanical systems, thermal science, and materials and manufacturing.
And it's easier for me to describe the areas by referring back to these groups or the research, because I remember what's going on there.
Starting with the design area, our major push right now is in the computer-aided design area.
We have purchased a new computer.
We're very involved in, we prefer to call it computer-aided engineering, but we're very involved in simulation, in kinematics development as it relates to robotics.
We're involved in finite elements, structural analysis, fracture mechanics.
We do a lot of work relating to oil field problems.
a major international symposium on piping design and stress analysis.
So those are some of the things that that group's involved in.
The mechanical systems group is involved in vibrations, acoustics, rotor dynamics, research in all these areas.
We have a substantial program going with the Veterans Administration right now to build devices related
to improving the utility of handicapped people, to control systems and let's say robotics-type systems for allowing handicapped people to drive automobiles.
We are involved in some SEALs work, if this makes sense, relating to very high
RPM load situations that would typically be involved.
The work came out of the engine for the new spacecraft.
And so this is very high energy pumps that require some very basic research in what's going on in the seals and the bearings.
We're doing a lot of work in bearing research for NASA.
We are just getting a brand new NSF project, which will be starting next
month and some very basic research in rotor dynamics and instability problems associated with rotor dynamics.
A major effort we're making in that group is we're on the verge of establishing a robotics laboratory.
And we are doing research in that area now.
We anticipate within a year or two from now we'll be one of the major research institutions in the country, hopefully.
In the thermal science area, that's the largest as far as the number of people.
It's very diverse.
We typically look at it as thermal science and thermal systems.
Thermal science, we're doing very basic research in fluid mechanics, looking at turbulence, noise generation from turbulent jets, structure of turbulent jets, things of this sort.
